And there's my email as
well, MaGabrielaG@me.com,

00:34:24.520 --> 00:34:27.310
with only one L.
This has been great.

00:34:29.100 --> 00:34:34.190
Thank you very much to
everyone that made it possible.

00:34:34.190 --> 00:34:36.910
And I don't know if
we have any questions.

00:34:41.756 --> 00:34:45.299
 <v Amanda> Thank you, Gaby, for that
masterclass in usability testing.

00:34:45.300 --> 00:34:48.460
It is now time for
the audience Q&amp;A.

00:34:48.460 --> 00:34:51.910
If you haven't had the
chance to put your question,

00:34:51.910 --> 00:34:55.420
you are welcome to add
that into the Q&amp;A section.

00:34:57.490 --> 00:35:03.770
And I am going to go ahead and
just ask the first question.

00:35:06.640 --> 00:35:08.380
During the ‘planning
period,’ you spoke

00:35:08.380 --> 00:35:15.390
about choosing the most
important scenarios on a site.

00:35:15.390 --> 00:35:21.180
Could you speak more about how
to do this?  <v Gaby> Absolutely.

00:35:21.180 --> 00:35:27.410
Let's say that you have a
system where you have to log in,

00:35:27.410 --> 00:35:32.230
and the most important thing that
you have to do is to print reports,

00:35:32.230 --> 00:35:32.990
right?

00:35:32.990 --> 00:35:37.520
But you also can personalize
the experience of your user,

00:35:37.520 --> 00:35:41.404
change your username,
and all of these things related

00:35:41.405 --> 00:35:42.770
to administration.

00:35:42.770 --> 00:35:49.010
In that case, I would first of
all test that the participant,

00:35:49.010 --> 00:35:53.690
the user, the people can actually
find reports and print reports.

00:35:55.150 --> 00:36:00.710
To do that, I have to, myself,
prior to the start of the test,

00:36:00.710 --> 00:36:07.300
log in and do some things in the
administrative task so that it is OK

00:36:07.300 --> 00:36:12.020
to start from a point of a
particular task, so that we make sure

00:36:12.020 --> 00:36:15.130
that we test what is the
most important thing.

00:36:15.130 --> 00:36:19.380
And then we go with
the fewer priorities.

00:36:22.660 --> 00:36:23.500
 <v Amanda> Wonderful.

00:36:23.500 --> 00:36:24.930
Thank you.

00:36:24.930 --> 00:36:29.110
Another question that
Anonymous had submitted is:

00:36:29.110 --> 00:36:32.120
You talked about the
report on a slide.

00:36:32.120 --> 00:36:35.067
Where or what is this?

00:36:35.067 --> 00:36:36.070
 <v Gaby> Yes.

00:36:36.070 --> 00:36:39.590
The report is that this is a test

00:36:39.591 --> 00:36:44.409
where you will learn many
things, right?

00:36:44.410 --> 00:36:49.930
So the report is the
summary of what you did.

00:36:49.930 --> 00:36:52.670
I wanted to have this goal.

00:36:52.670 --> 00:36:54.630
I wanted to learn this.

00:36:54.630 --> 00:36:56.710
I selected these participants.

00:36:56.710 --> 00:36:59.870
This is the characteristics
of my participants.

00:36:59.870 --> 00:37:02.910
This is the task,
the scenarios that I wanted to test.

00:37:02.910 --> 00:37:04.290
This was my environment.

00:37:04.290 --> 00:37:05.660
These are the metrics.

00:37:05.660 --> 00:37:08.150
You list everything on the test.

00:37:08.150 --> 00:37:11.590
Then, This is what I learnt.
These are my findings.

00:37:11.590 --> 00:37:14.730
I decided to
prioritize it this way.

00:37:15.800 --> 00:37:19.660
And these are the things
that I will fix first.

00:37:19.660 --> 00:37:22.300
So it's like a summary
of what you did.

00:37:22.300 --> 00:37:26.620
It's like taking a picture of all
the efforts that you're making

00:37:26.620 --> 00:37:29.520
so that you first have it, right?

00:37:29.520 --> 00:37:32.040
We cannot measure
what we don't have.

00:37:32.040 --> 00:37:34.750
We cannot improve
what we don't measure.

00:37:34.750 --> 00:37:36.810
So you will have it there.

00:37:36.810 --> 00:37:41.480
Also, you can use it as a
communication tool within your team,

00:37:41.480 --> 00:37:44.600
your organization,
because these are facts, you know.

00:37:44.600 --> 00:37:49.060
It’s not that, I think that
maybe this is not accessible.

00:37:49.060 --> 00:37:53.940
I know for a fact,
because 70% of the participants

00:37:53.940 --> 00:37:56.270
couldn't complete this task.

00:37:56.270 --> 00:37:58.500
It’s also a picture
for you to compare.

00:37:58.500 --> 00:38:01.600
You go, you improve what
you have to improve.

00:38:01.600 --> 00:38:05.380
You do more testing,
and you compare the first version

00:38:05.380 --> 00:38:06.600
versus the second version.

00:38:06.600 --> 00:38:11.130
So the report is to take a
picture in the form of a report,

00:38:11.130 --> 00:38:12.040
a presentation.

00:38:12.040 --> 00:38:15.110
If you Google,
The Common Industry Format

00:38:15.110 --> 00:38:19.700
for Usability Testing
is a great way to do it.

00:38:23.752 --> 00:38:25.240
 <v Amanda> Thank you.

00:38:25.240 --> 00:38:30.200
Another question, moving along,
is: Is it a good idea to ask

00:38:30.200 --> 00:38:34.930
at the end of the engagement
how you did as a tester,

00:38:34.930 --> 00:38:37.090
and what the feedback might be?

00:38:37.090 --> 00:38:39.020
Or is that not professional?

00:38:39.020 --> 00:38:43.040
It would help testers become more
competent and provide more value

00:38:43.040 --> 00:38:44.040
to the clients.

00:38:44.040 --> 00:38:46.250
 <v Gaby> It's perfectly good.

00:38:46.250 --> 00:38:48.830
I suggest you do it on a survey.

00:38:48.830 --> 00:38:54.800
You can do it on a paper
survey, on an accessible link

00:38:54.800 --> 00:38:56.420
for the participants.

00:38:56.420 --> 00:39:00.940
If you have help depending on
your team or a friend of yours,

00:39:00.940 --> 00:39:04.640
you can have another
station with a device ready

00:39:04.640 --> 00:39:07.190
to take that final thoughts.

00:39:07.190 --> 00:39:10.110
Just to prevent the
participants to feel, you know,

00:39:10.110 --> 00:39:13.700
maybe you were talking too
fast, and they want to say that,

00:39:13.700 --> 00:39:17.170
but they don't want
to make you feel sad.

00:39:17.170 --> 00:39:20.230
Because I have learned that
participants are so great

00:39:20.230 --> 00:39:23.070
that they have you in their minds.

00:39:23.070 --> 00:39:26.560
So just make sure that it's
something that is anonymous.

00:39:26.560 --> 00:39:29.800
Some people will do it because they
want to, but it's not unprofessional

00:39:29.800 --> 00:39:30.580
in my opinion.

00:39:30.580 --> 00:39:35.380
I would always request also
feedback of me as a facilitator.

00:39:39.234 --> 00:39:40.190
 <v Amanda> Good question.

00:39:41.730 --> 00:39:45.100
Do you think in-house testing,
meaning with your own team

00:39:45.100 --> 00:39:47.964
or the client,
is better than no testing

00:39:47.965 --> 00:39:50.130
when you might not have access

00:39:50.130 --> 00:39:54.100
to or the resources/budget
for outside testers?

00:39:54.100 --> 00:39:56.150
 <v Gaby> Definitely.

00:39:56.150 --> 00:39:57.910
I’ll say this.

00:39:57.910 --> 00:40:01.340
If you have a roommate,
if you live with your parent,

00:40:01.340 --> 00:40:06.520
if you have a neighbor,
even that is better than nothing.

00:40:06.520 --> 00:40:07.780
Within the organization?

00:40:07.780 --> 00:40:08.780
Of course.

00:40:10.560 --> 00:40:17.030
The first thing that we actually
do in my team is to test inside,

00:40:17.030 --> 00:40:20.660
because there are things
that are not usable,

00:40:20.660 --> 00:40:26.250
and they are these big issues
that you want to make sure

00:40:26.250 --> 00:40:28.610
that you cover with friends.

00:40:28.610 --> 00:40:32.060
Let's say with friends and
family, meaning the organization,

00:40:32.060 --> 00:40:36.010
your teammates, people in the
organization that is not involved

00:40:36.010 --> 00:40:38.560
in that product or project.

00:40:38.560 --> 00:40:39.790
So definitely.

00:40:39.790 --> 00:40:45.460
And then with that, you will find
the biggest errors that you have.

00:40:45.460 --> 00:40:48.610
And when you have the time
and the budget, or you find

00:40:48.610 --> 00:40:54.030
to make a connection or something,
you can test for accessibility

00:40:54.030 --> 00:40:59.620
in depth or usability, but things
that you know that are not really bad

00:40:59.620 --> 00:41:01.430
because you already tested.

00:41:03.330 --> 00:41:05.090
Always test.

00:41:05.090 --> 00:41:06.900
That's the summary.

00:41:06.900 --> 00:41:07.460
Always test.

00:41:11.194 --> 00:41:12.240
 <v Amanda> It's a great takeaway.

00:41:13.520 --> 00:41:16.710
Another question
from Ron: Do you try

00:41:16.710 --> 00:41:21.740
to verify the voluntary product
accessibility template information

00:41:21.740 --> 00:41:25.990
from vendors,
from usability testing perspective?

00:41:25.990 --> 00:41:30.770
And if so, do you find that
VPATs are usually reliable?

00:41:32.072 --> 00:41:35.420
 <v Gaby> In my experience,
VPATs are reliable.

00:41:36.810 --> 00:41:42.970
And this depends on the
organization that you hire

00:41:42.970 --> 00:41:46.220
or you're working with to do so.

00:41:46.220 --> 00:41:49.750
I have worked with
organizations because, you know,

00:41:49.750 --> 00:41:53.940
it's a very good way
to have a third-party,

00:41:53.940 --> 00:41:58.210
somebody that is not
involved, to do these reviews.

00:41:59.900 --> 00:42:04.010
When we compare this with
our own things, of course,

00:42:04.010 --> 00:42:06.140
we learn things from
other perspectives.

00:42:06.140 --> 00:42:08.250
Tests will always
give you learnings.

00:42:09.320 --> 00:42:12.300
But in my personal opinion,
these are very reliable.

00:42:14.080 --> 00:42:17.980
Of course, we do research
about who will do this, right?

00:42:17.980 --> 00:42:19.390
So that's important.

00:42:27.333 --> 00:42:29.997
[crosstalk 00:42:26]

00:42:29.998 --> 00:42:33.320
 <v Amanda> Another question from
Ron: When doing usability testing,

00:42:33.320 --> 00:42:38.100
what's the smallest number of testers
you feel provides a good range

00:42:38.100 --> 00:42:41.660
of feedback to catch the majority
of challenges on a website?

00:42:41.660 --> 00:42:44.990
 <v Gaby> That is a great
question, and thank you.

00:42:46.390 --> 00:42:53.870
There is a theory that is
presented in a mathematical way.

00:42:53.870 --> 00:42:56.920
I am not an expert and that's
why I will not dive into that.

00:42:58.660 --> 00:43:04.870
This model I can share
in the chat later.

00:43:04.870 --> 00:43:09.060
But if you test with five people,
you will find most of your problems.

00:43:10.350 --> 00:43:14.660
What happens if you test with
the first one, you find problems;

00:43:14.660 --> 00:43:17.610
you test with the second
participant, you find those problems

00:43:17.610 --> 00:43:18.610
and a little bit more.

00:43:19.620 --> 00:43:23.310
You try with the third one,
and you find what you already found.

00:43:23.310 --> 00:43:26.880
So by the number five,
you’ve pretty much found everything

00:43:26.880 --> 00:43:28.550
on that iteration.

00:43:28.550 --> 00:43:33.980
If you're testing for performance,
for usability in a performance,

00:43:33.980 --> 00:43:37.950
environment, or if you want to
make sure that you find trends

00:43:37.950 --> 00:43:41.680
or stuff like that,
go with bigger amounts.

00:43:41.680 --> 00:43:45.710
But, because this is
meant to be a starter for you,

00:43:45.710 --> 00:43:48.690
to inspire you, five people.

00:43:48.690 --> 00:43:52.790
But again,
one is more than zero; it's better.

00:43:54.510 --> 00:43:55.730
But five is the answer.

00:43:58.267 --> 00:43:59.430
 <v Amanda> That
sounds really doable.

00:44:02.450 --> 00:44:06.900
Another question is: How do you
make sure your test is flexible

00:44:06.900 --> 00:44:11.860
for people of all abilities,
your questions, and the tasks;

00:44:11.860 --> 00:44:15.590
including screen reader, tabbing
versus scrolling through the site?

00:44:18.300 --> 00:44:21.890
 <v Gaby> You don't know if
your site is accessible, right?

00:44:21.890 --> 00:44:24.010
So you want to find that out.

00:44:24.010 --> 00:44:28.060
If you follow the guidelines,
if you research about it,

00:44:28.060 --> 00:44:31.170
you will know what not
to do from the start.

00:44:32.750 --> 00:44:35.327
But,
in order to make the questions

00:44:35.328 --> 00:44:37.150
and how to perform the test,

00:44:37.150 --> 00:44:42.140
my suggestion is to find somebody
from the community of accessibility,

00:44:42.140 --> 00:44:45.620
or a person with
disability and ask them.

00:44:46.720 --> 00:44:51.860
For me, I want to share
that sometimes I don’t know,

00:44:51.860 --> 00:44:56.030
and I still don't know how to say
certain things, how to express

00:44:56.030 --> 00:44:57.200
in some environments.

00:44:57.200 --> 00:45:01.020
And I always ask because
it's the honest thing to do.

00:45:01.020 --> 00:45:04.290
I apologize,
I don't know I want to learn.

00:45:04.290 --> 00:45:08.660
Please help me. And I guarantee
somebody will support you.

00:45:08.660 --> 00:45:11.840
So if you go to the
community, again...

00:45:11.840 --> 00:45:16.150
And this is why it's so important,
the inclusive collaboration.

00:45:16.150 --> 00:45:18.900
People will help you
and guide you with that.

00:45:18.900 --> 00:45:24.140
There are some websites that
have suggestions on what to do

00:45:24.140 --> 00:45:25.350
and what to do.

00:45:25.350 --> 00:45:30.630
Perkins School For The Blind,
and Perkins Access, I can say

00:45:30.630 --> 00:45:34.610
that they have a pretty
good set of guidelines on

00:45:34.610 --> 00:45:38.750
how to do this type of exercises.

00:45:38.750 --> 00:45:40.350
So maybe you can
also check that out.

00:45:46.612 --> 00:45:47.760
 <v Amanda> Great resource.

00:45:48.900 --> 00:45:50.780
A question from
Christine [phonetic]:

00:45:50.780 --> 00:45:55.150
Could you provide some examples
of where the WCAG falls short?

00:46:00.225 --> 00:46:03.910
 <v Gaby> In my experience,
there are some guidelines

00:46:03.910 --> 00:46:05.700
that are complex for me.

00:46:05.700 --> 00:46:12.140
I don't know if it is my English,
but there are some guidelines that,

00:46:12.140 --> 00:46:15.890
since I don't really understand,
I don't know how to apply.

00:46:15.890 --> 00:46:18.180
I don't know how to build it.

00:46:18.180 --> 00:46:23.340
So I maybe don't have, right now,
an example that comes to mind,

00:46:23.340 --> 00:46:27.060
but for sure, what I have
experience is, I don't know

00:46:27.060 --> 00:46:28.800
how that translates into something.

00:46:28.800 --> 00:46:33.250
So I either test to double
check and make sure,

00:46:33.250 --> 00:46:38.830
or ask the community,
or my co-workers, or somebody that,

00:46:38.830 --> 00:46:43.990
maybe, in a more technical way,
understands the guidelines.

00:46:45.280 --> 00:46:50.370
My biggest example is the real
life scenario that I presented,

00:46:50.370 --> 00:46:54.100
where sometimes you follow
guidelines and they are great,

00:46:54.100 --> 00:46:57.640
but they just don’t really apply
out there in the real world.

00:47:00.270 --> 00:47:05.010
But I find, as an example,
that's a good one for the future.

00:47:05.010 --> 00:47:06.540
 <v Amanda> Wonderful.

00:47:06.540 --> 00:47:09.670
We have two more questions
and then we'll wrap up.

00:47:09.670 --> 00:47:14.540
We have a question from John:
Don't you think having a better

00:47:14.540 --> 00:47:18.550
and cleaner code from the foundation
of your project helps you build

00:47:18.550 --> 00:47:20.570
a better and less receptible

00:47:20.570 --> 00:47:25.180
to testing for better reliability?
 <v Gaby> One-hundred-percent.

00:47:26.350 --> 00:47:31.880
Building accessible sites,
when you follow the guidelines,

00:47:31.880 --> 00:47:36.550
by default, immediately,
your code is 100%.

00:47:42.070 --> 00:47:45.923
So my suggestion to
developers all the time is,

00:47:45.924 --> 00:47:48.090
this is good for everyone.

00:47:48.090 --> 00:47:51.730
Accessibility is an umbrella
that covers everyone.

00:47:56.528 --> 00:47:57.420
 <v Amanda> Absolutely.

00:47:58.940 --> 00:48:03.320
One last question from Luna: Do
you have any additional resources

00:48:03.320 --> 00:48:08.150
